{"title":"Using the Console","markdown":{"headingText":"Using the Console","headingAttr":{"id":"sec-console","classes":[],"keyvalue":[]},"containsRefs":false,"markdown":"\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-problem}\n**The Problem**\n\nYou're in a meeting and your supervisor asks, out loud: \"Quick — if we enrolled 120 participants and 18 dropped out, what percentage completed the study?\" Everyone's looking at you. You don't want to open a whole new script file, name it, and save it just to answer one quick question.\n:::\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-mission}\n**Your Mission**\n\nUse the RStudio Console to run a one-off calculation immediately, without creating or saving a file.\n:::\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-think}\n**Think Before Coding**\n\n- What's the actual arithmetic needed to turn \"102 out of 120 completed\" into a percentage?\n- Does this calculation need to be saved for later, or is it truly a one-time question?\n:::\n\n## The R Concept\n\nThe **Console** is the pane where R code runs immediately and directly — you type a line, press Enter, and see the result right away. Nothing you type there is automatically saved anywhere as a file. This makes the Console perfect for:\n\n- Quick, one-off calculations\n- Checking what a function does before using it in a real script\n- Peeking at an object's value in the middle of a longer analysis\n\nIt's a poor choice for anything you'll want to rerun, hand to a colleague, or revisit next month — for that, you want a script (next page).\n\nYou can tell you're in the Console because it has a `>` prompt at the start of the line, waiting for input. Type your code after the `>` and press **Enter** to run it.\n\n## Demonstration\n\nTyped directly into the Console:\n\n```r\n> 102 / 120 * 100\n```\n\n```\n[1] 85\n```\n\nYou can also press the **up arrow** key in the Console to recall the previous command, edit it, and rerun it — useful when your supervisor immediately follows up with \"okay, now what if it's 110 out of 120?\"\n\n```r\n> 110 / 120 * 100\n```\n\n```\n[1] 91.66667\n```\n\n## Explore\n\nIn the Console, calculate what percentage 18 out of 120 represents — the dropout rate rather than the completion rate. Then use the up-arrow to recall that line and change `18` to `25`. Notice how much faster this is than retyping the whole line.\n\n## Solve the Problem\n\nBack in the meeting, you type directly into the Console:\n\n```r\n> 102 / 120 * 100\n[1] 85\n```\n\nYou answer immediately: \"85% of participants completed the study.\" No file needed, no saving required — exactly the right use of the Console.\n\n## Interpret the Result\n\n`85` means that of the 120 enrolled participants, 85 out of every 100 (equivalently, 102 out of 120) completed the study — an 85% completion rate, which is generally considered a strong retention rate in longitudinal health research.\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-mistake}\n**Common Mistakes**\n\n- **Doing important, reusable analysis only in the Console.** If you'll need this calculation again — for a report, for next month's update — put it in a script instead (next page).\n- **Losing track of what was run.** The Console's History tab keeps a record, but it's not as organized or intentional as a saved script with comments explaining each step.\n- **Forgetting the calculation entirely once the Console is cleared or RStudio is closed.** Nothing in the Console is saved unless you explicitly copy it elsewhere.\n:::\n\n## Practice Problem\n\nIn the Console, calculate the percentage of a study where 340 out of 400 participants returned for a 6-month follow-up visit.\n\n## Challenge Problem\n\nYour supervisor now asks a follow-up: \"What if we'd also included 40 participants who transferred to another clinic?\" Using the up-arrow to build on your previous answer, calculate the new completion percentage out of a total of 440 enrolled, assuming the same 340 completed.\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n- The Console runs code immediately but does not save it as a file.\n- Use the Console for quick, one-off questions — not for analysis you'll need to reproduce or share.\n- The up-arrow key recalls previous commands in the Console, which speeds up rapid back-and-forth questions.\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-check}\n**Knowledge Check**\n\n1. **Multiple choice.** The Console is best suited for:\n   a) Long-term, reusable analysis scripts\n   b) Quick, one-off calculations and checks\n   c) Storing your final report\n   d) Installing RStudio itself\n\n2. **True or false.** Code typed into the Console is automatically saved as a file when you close RStudio.\n\n3. **Predict the output.**\n   ```r\n   45 / 60 * 100\n   ```\n\n4. **Write the code.** Write the Console command to calculate what percentage 7 is of 28.\n\n<details class=\"pbl-answer\">\n<summary>Show answers</summary>\n\n1. **b)** Quick, one-off calculations and checks.\n2. **False.** Console input is not saved as a file; only scripts you explicitly save are preserved.\n3. `[1] 75`\n4. `7 / 28 * 100`, which evaluates to `[1] 25`.\n\n</details>\n:::\n","srcMarkdownNoYaml":""},"formats":{"html":{"identifier":{"display-name":"HTML","target-format":"html","base-format":"html"},"execute":{"fig-width":7,"fig-height":5,"fig-format":"retina","fig-dpi":96,"df-print":"default","error":false,"eval":true,"cache":null,"freeze":"auto","echo":true,"output":true,"warning":false,"include":true,"keep-md":false,"keep-ipynb":false,"ipynb":null,"enabled":null,"daemon":null,"daemon-restart":false,"debug":false,"ipynb-filters":[],"ipynb-shell-interactivity":null,"plotly-connected":true,"message":false,"engine":"markdown"},"render":{"keep-tex":false,"keep-typ":false,"keep-source":false,"keep-hidden":false,"prefer-html":false,"output-divs":true,"output-ext":"html","fig-align":"default","fig-pos":null,"fig-env":null,"code-fold":false,"code-overflow":"scroll","code-link":true,"code-line-numbers":false,"code-tools":true,"tbl-colwidths":"auto","merge-includes":true,"inline-includes":false,"preserve-yaml":false,"latex-auto-mk":true,"latex-auto-insta